May 8 2008 	Keno Tournament at Fitzgerald's Casino Las Vegas	Just returned from a Keno tournament in Las Vegas at Fitzgerald's Hotel and Casino, and we can't wait to go back! The hotel is in the &quot;old&quot; part of town, right at the beginning of the Fremont Street Experience. Anytime I get THREE NIGHTS FREE, which we did with the tournament, I think it's excellent!The hotel itself is a bit tattered and worn (but clean) - and the ventilation systems are not quite as good as the newer casinos. Things feel a bit &quot;tighter&quot; than in the sprawling taj mahals on the strip. But overall, the good outweighs the bad. The staff is extremely helpful and friendly, for one thing. The buffet is very good and free drinks are served often. There is a Walgreen's Drug store steps from the front door. And best of all, when you play in a tournament, you get three nights' room absolutely FREE. In addition, (and I assume this applies to other tournaments), we received four meal vouchers (for the player in the tournament and a partner) and two other tournament meals, an evening buffet and a breakfast, and player shirts. Now, HOW GREAT IS THAT??The keno tournament is held 4 times a year, but they also host other tournament events, which, I am guessing, have similar perks. In the keno tournament, you put up $500, but get the full amount back to play in the tournament, and you get to keep all your winnings. Of the approximately 100 players, about 1/4 earned all their money back. The top winner took home over $11,000. We met some &quot;regulars&quot; at the tournament who said, &quot;Why stay on the strip when the only thing I need my room for is to sleep?&quot; The sleeping rooms are adequate, the beds very firm, and the shower was hot. Depending on the time of day, the four elevators could be slow, but that's true with any high-rise hotel. For those unfamiliar with Fremont Street, it is 5 blocks of pedestrian mall with a 1,400 foot canopy light show - billed as the world's largest. It's unlike anything you've ever seen. Also available in the mall area are small shops, drug stores, other casinos, and restaurants - all within easy walking distance, unlike the strip. There is nightly entertainment outside your front door.The Deuce Bus, which runs the length of the strip, is available for $5/day, so it's easy to get out to the other end of the strip if you want to tour other casinos or go to a show. So, check out Fitzgerald's Casino. Las Vegas deals are still there, if you know where to look! Go to the other end of the strip for glitz and glamour and giant pools, but go to Fitzgeralds to have fun, save a buck, and win a bunch!	
