Sep 4 2007	The Fitz is ok for the price	Stayed at the Fitz for four nights last week of August 2007. This was my first downtown experience. There are plus and minuses at this property that was supposedly renovated a few years ago. My room was on the 24th floor with a fair northly view. Although the room was supposedly non-smoking there is some tobacco smell (perhaps coming from the floor below?) but it's not strong. The room is good sized, bedding and towels clean, two queen sized beds were rather firm and the mattresses seem new. No bedbugs. I could not tell if the carpeting had been recently steam cleaned because it was a dark shade (chocolate) but walking on it with bare feet was ok. The carpeting is coming up in spots. There is a secure wall safe w/key (no deposit), a hair dryer, and iron/ironing borad. The room lighting is adequate but one ceiling light needed a new bulb. The television is ok but the choice of channels is limited. Closet space good. Furniture is ok and not worn. The bathroom was clean and there is plenty of counterspace for personal toiletries. The hotel provides your basic soap and shampoo and these were adequate. Lack of an exhaust fan means that moisture will remain on the walls and ceiling, which in turn means mold. Just abit of mold above the shower. A serious problem is the shower curtain. Some idiot did not include a plastic curtain to go with the fabric one which means water on the floor every time I used the shower. I had to use a bath towel to sop up water. One good slip on the floor and you can say lawsuit! The shower faucet had a leak (waste of water). Unlike other hotels in Las Vegas the Fitz does not seem ecology minded (they don't ask guests to conserve water and reuse towels). The air conditioner was fine and not too noisy and does help cover some of the music from the Fremont Experience. The Fitz badly needs window washing. The exterior corridors are clean with less wear or wall marks than I have seen at some upscale hotels including the Luxor. Major problem is the elevators. Only three of the four were in operation and a few times I waited for 10 minutes for one. This could be a big problem in a medical emergency (there are separate service elevators not accessible to the public). The hotel itself is clean and fairly easy to navigate. The casino seems easily accessible for those who are handicapped (not so in certain other hotels). Directional signage could be improved. One good thing is that the hotel/casino is not so big that one spends 20 minutes getting to a restaurant. There are some entertainment options that I did not partake. The buffet is closed until later in Sept. The restaurant does not have a huge selection or variety on the menu but it 's not too expensive and the portions are large. My one big complaint is that sometimes noise from renovations in the buffet area can interfere with eating (why not give some discounts for the trouble). Oh yes. This is not a 24 hour restaurant except on weekends; other times there is McDonalds. The steakhouse looks good but I did not try the food (reservations suggested and I suggest dressing up some). The Vue bar has outdoor seating above street level. It has appetizers that come from the restaurant.Customer service is good and staff seem friendlier than at hotels on the Strip. Housekeeping did a good job. I had no problems with check-in or check-out but then there were no lines of people. My overall impression is that the Fitz is ok for the budget minded and especially if one gets a cheap package deal. It is close to the Duece bus stop. I won't comment on the gambling but as nearby gaming options are easily walkable the Fitz has a good location. Fitzgeralds compares in quality to the Riviera but is less expensive. I hope they add some elevators, and please, get a good shower curtain!	
Sep 2 2007 	Overall "great"	I have stayed downtown Vegas for at least the last 10 years. First it was Lady Luck, then when it became run-down, I chose to try Fitzgeralds. Been going there ever since. I recommend this property to anyone who goes to Vegas to gamble and walk to other casinos. If it was a honeymooner, or first time young person they belong on the strip. I don't need the BIG casinos, and I can't walk the distance of the strip like I did years ago. Fitzgeralds has the restaurants, casino, and neat/clean rooms. Everyone whom told about this hotel has stayed there and thought it was great. Being able to walk to other casinos, and feel safe about it, is one of the best things about downtown. We rent a car, travel around, back to Fitzgeralds, and enjoy the Fremont experience. Also, the price is right!	
