Dec 12 2006 	Great hotel questionable housekeeping	Our first trip to Las Vegas we stayed at the Fitzgerald. It was, for the most part, great. We checked in with some of the friendliest hotel staff that I had the pleasure of dealing with. Sandra was hilarious and very helpful. There were only two problems that we encountered on a daily basis. There were three of us staying at the hotel on the 27th floor and the shower dripped all 5 days we were there and the housekeeping couldn't seem to understand that if you have 3 guests in the room, you need towels, coffee etc. for 3 people on a daily basis, not two! We had to call every single day we were there for enough amenities for 3 people. Other than that, the place was clean, well lit, very quiet and the view was spectacular. We felt safe in the lobby, even at 4:00 in the morning when my sister and I were by ourself. We never did get to try Limericks. It was closed and under renos every time we went. The breakfast buffet was fabulous with helpful chefs at two stations to make your fresh omelettes. Prices were reasonable at Molly's and the staff were friendly and on their toes giving good service. Security could be seen almost everywhere you looked. We did not break the bank while we were there but plan on going back to try again this October. I would recommend this place to anyone who wants to stay off the hustle and bustle of the Strip and sit on the balcony with a cold one while watching the Fremont Experience.	
Dec 9 2006 	A decent choice but check out GN Here's why...	Not a bad hotel at all. I'd give it a solid &quot;3 stars. &quot; I got a room on the 16th floor which had some pretty good views of the Strip and surrounding mountains. The room was clean and good sized. The decor was fairly spartan and could use updating. Good sized bathroom with a whirlpool tub for one. One of the least impressive casinos downtown. Although they have a bank of the best nickle videopoker machines I've ever played! They're called something like &quot;video wheel&quot; poker. They're right down from the bell desk against the wall. Bet 20 coins- $1.00. Everytime you get a winning hand the machine allows you to &quot;double down&quot; by picking one of two colors. The wheel spins and if it lands on your color you double your winnings. You can keep trying to double your winnings. Believe me; there's no pattern to which color the wheel lands on, no matter what you think! However, this way, you can make a &quot;killing&quot; (if you're lucky) on a &quot;jacks or better&quot; win, which with every other VP machine simply gives you back your original bet. If you get a &quot;full house&quot; the wheel spins and you have a shot at up to $25,000 in cash. Best thing is ALL these VP machines were &quot;loose&quot; when I played them. If you're good, you can play a very long time on $20.00 dreaming of the spin for the big prize. I got a &quot;full house&quot; three times but when you see the wheel spin and miss the big bucks, that's when you know it's not &quot;random.&quot; Still, it's the best VP I've played in years. I went to all the casinos to see if there was a twenty-five cent version; didn't see any. The dinner buffer was merely fair. Much better ones on Fremont. The best thing about this hotel is that it's right on Fremont St with the &quot;Fremont Experience&quot; right outside the door. No exercise facilities at this hotel. Go two hotels down to Golden Nugget. For $20.00 you can get a day pass to their spa/exercise. You'll feel &quot;rich&quot; surrounded by the elegance of the spa itself. Full use of locker room (stocked with healthy snacks) get a plush robe, etc. It's classy with all the amenities you would find at the 4-5 star hotels on the strip. In fact, this property feels like a Strip resort rather than merely a hotel/casino. If the prices are the same as other hotels, THIS is the place to stay downtown!	
Nov 18 2006	Room 323	Fitzgeralds room 323 was at the end of the hall across from the stairs and just below and adjacent to the Fremont street experience. The room is about 130 away from the elevator. The window view is a ground roof view of the roof and an angle view of the FSE metal cover. Standing on your toes you can see the corner of the Fitzgeralds balcony bar. The Nov. rising sun provides plenty on reading light in the low wattage room. You can hear the bass of the Fremont Street Experience. The sound is not real bothersome to me with the air conditioner and TV on. I did not have a problem sleeping, but most people will be bothered. The stairs next to the room come out on the 1st floor inside the high roller roped off area, but that was not useful to me. I could not find a door to the second floor on the stairs. The rooms above (423 &amp; 523 maybe) on floors 4 &amp; 5 dirextly abone appear to have a curved window in the corner of the room, while 323 does not. Fitzgeralds does not have in room internet access, but does have a public (pay?) room downstairs. I could pick up the free wireless signal from Crispi Kreme on the first floor, but it was too weak for me to use. A signal booster might make it work since the donut shop is directly under the room. The TV has a few more channels than other downtown Vegas hotels, still no favorite premium channels but the channels are:2.KVMY My Network TV3.KVBC  NBC4.C-SPAN  II5.KVVU FOX6.In room KENO7.TBS Atlanta8.KLAS CBS9.Univision Spanish10.PBS KLVX11.WGN Chicago12.USA13.KTNV  ABC14.CNBC15.MSNBC16.ESPN17.CNN18.Fitzgerald Channel20.Hotel Info21.Hotel Info22.LV Tourism Convention23.Classical Radio24.Country Radio25.Rock Radio26.News Radio27.NBC KVBC Channel 3 LV22.There were (3) adult channels that played free around the clock, which was a real surprise. I noticed you could also purchase them, but they were free in this room on channels 37, 38, and 39. There is also a control lockout for parent or wife. The room had a tiny one cup (10 oz) coffee maker in the bathroom. The small tea or coffee bags with a string will work perfect in it if you bring some. Other fixtures: Ironing board, king bed, iron, free key safe, proterra shampoo, conditioner, lotion, facial bar soap, and large oatmeal bath soap, 2 large towels, 2 medium towels, 2 wash cloths, 3 ash trays, ice bowl with 6 cups, 2 coffee cups, 9 coat hangers, complicated alarm radio clock, king bed with 3 pillows, one closet pillow, 4 diameter wood table, 2 chairs, one sofa chair, large 2 drawer dresser, 3 drawer wood entertainment center, (2) one drawer night stands, 3 lamps, 2 trash cans, 3 phone books, phone with $1 per call, Philips 29 regular screen TV/remote, in room movies $10.99 each, smoke detector, fire alarm, 3 fire sprinklers, tissues, 3 mirrors, 2 pictures, tissues, and of course toilet paper and bible. I left $1 in the bible for you. The air conditioner could keep the room extremely cold and the fan noise moving the air was the only loud sound. The room was roughly about 30X17 including the bathroom. Fitzgeralds has no room service, no hair dryer, and only two electric wall plugs. They do have checkout available on the TV. The hall had a $1.50 20 oz drink machine and a free ice machine. Mollys Buffet is minimal selection, but has an omelet chef in morning until 11 AM. Buffet breakfast has 2 boxed cereals, make your toast, hash browns, 2 sausages, milk, 5 juices, sodas, 5 pastries/muffins, 2 scrambled eggs, bacon, minimal fruit, and jelly. Coupons are available for Mollys at check in and at the front door in the evening. The Fremont and Golden Nugget Buffet are larger. Mollys Caf is small but has excellent service and a $9.99 steak &amp; shrimp. The 4 Queens, Golden Nugget, and Horseshoe caf are better. Smoking is still allowed in specific areas the restaurant, but city laws are expected to isolate smokers soon in all LV city restaurants. MacDonalds is downstairs with $1 double cheeseburgers, $1 sundaes, 1$ frys, 2 for $1 pies, $1 spicy chicken burger, and $3.99 big macs.	
