Nov 17 2005	Friendly clean and cheap	First of all, if you've never been to Las Vegas, don't expect glamor and gangster hip...it isn't there. If you don't like gambling and watching people gorge themselves at buffets, this may well not be the place for you. On the other hand, this is a great - and inexpensive - place from which to base yourself if you are exploring National Parks. Death Valley, Zion, Bryce and the Grand Canyon are all within a few hours drive. In addition, Red Rocks Canyon Conservation Area - a BLM managed area - is a BEAUTIFUL place to hike, with intimate views of red sandstone formations, and long vistas that are usually found in National Parks. So on to Fitzgerald's. We paid 175 dollars per person to fly from Seattle to Vegas...that price included 3 nights at Fitzgerald's - a tourist class hotel in downtown Las Vegas. From check-in to check-out, the staff was remarkably friendly and went out of their way to make us feel welcomed. Our room was on the 32nd floor, providing amazing views to the West. Housekeeping staff were thorough and timely, the restaurant staff was extremely friendly, and the food was pretty good value, particularly the breakfast buffet (other meals served at the buffet looked less appetizing. The only thing about staying downtown is that some rooms - even ours on the 32nd floor - are subject to noise from the lightshow/music stages on Fremont Street. This was a very minor inconvenience, solved by turning on the fan in the room. If you get a really good deal, stay here. It's nice enough. Otherwise, try the Golden Nugget - 4 star hotel at 2 star prices.	
