Sep 27 2005	Comfort in Vegas	If you are a fan of classic downtown Vegas, you will enjoy staying at the Fitzgerald Hotel.It is located in the middle of the Fremont experience in downtown Vegas, and is in easy walking distance of a variety of nice hotel casinoes, with a good presence of security personnel who made my walking around the covered street, a safe and pleasant experience. The Fitzgerald has a decent buffet with prices less than ten dollars on weekdays The hotel also has a variety of weekend entertainment, including a house talent and skilled Elvis Tribute artist named Steve Connelly, who performed at a talent contest, the weekend I was there, and several other acts as well, on a rotating basis.The room I had at the Fitzgerald was clean, bright, well lit, and of a decent size. The bathroom was comfortable and well lit, and was clean and well stocked with complimentary items.The room had a safe where you could keep winnings or jewelry and valuables, and a good sized open wardrobe to hang your clothes and coats, and a good sized set of drawers for other clothing items. I found no indication that the cleaning staff got into my bags, and I was impressed with the well made and comfortable beds.The 24 hour Shamrock Cafe was okay for breakfast, but I was much more impressed with the food and service at the Binions Cafe across the street in the Binion's Casino, where I ate most of my meals. I was able to get a variety of breakfasts for 6 dollars of less, and a midnite special of four breakfasts at 3 dollars a piece. They even had a steak special for five dollars that was awesome. The Fremont buffet across the street was also a favorite lunch haunt, since they had a variety of seafood and excellent meats and vegetables for 8 dollars during the week, and 12 on the weekend. In the evening, a free light show is shown on the giant canopy over Fremont street, which I found entertaining, but which can disrupt your sleep if you have a room on the Fremont side of the Hotel, and go to bed before 11. If you wish to avoid renting an automobile, and want to see the Vegas Strip, the Route 106 shuttle can get you from the Walgeens at the end of Fremont Street to the Sahara, for less than 2 dollars, and the monorail can take you from the Sahara to a variety of other major strip hotels for 3 dollars a ride, or 10 dollars for a day pass.  The monorail travels the strip down to the MGM Grand, where you can take an elevated walkway to New York New York, and on to Excaliber. At Excalaber, you can catch a free shuttle monorail to Luxor and Mandalay Bay. If you decide to use the Fitzgerald, and want to avoid the cost of a taxi, the best bet is to book a reservation at one of the shuttle buses who service the airport. I used Showtime, but there are several companies with shuttles, and the average cost ranges from 11 to 12 dollars for a round trip shuttle ticket. Fitzgerald does not have a hotel shuttle service, as many of the strip hotels do, but the hotel expence is far less for the rooms. I stayed in a good room that went for 52 dollars a night but the strip hotels can cost 75 dollars a night or more.	
