Sep 4 2005 	The casino is fine...the hotel and restaurants need some help	Have stayed at the Fitz several times over the past 6-7 months during my frequent business trips into Las Vegas. The staff is friendly, for the most part (exception: Eric at the front desk - few words, no thank you, no smile, and sometimes an attitude - I'm &quot;lucky&quot; enough to get him at least 50% of the time!). The casino, although a bit dingy, is full of a variety of table games and some of the loosest slots I have played in my many trips to LV. A good choice of table games with low limits and friendly dealers.The cafe' upstairs is OK (probably a 5 on a 1-10 scale) and is somewhat pricey for the market it serves. The buffet is a miss...without question...it shouldn't qualify for a buffet in Las Vegas...maybe 2 choices of entrees, a couple of side choices, a small salad bar and perhaps 3 or 4 desserts to choose from...severely lacking by Vegas standards and not exactly cheap (lunch is about $8) given the selections you are offered (Stations casinos run lunch buffets for about $7 and give you 10X the options not to mention Main Street Station down the block). The McDonalds on the first floor is 24 hrs which is nice for that quick bite but they have been out of ice cream and milk shakes on at least 50% of my visits...seems poorly managed, a bit dirty, and less than efficient compared to most fast-food stops. A gift shop exists across from the front desk which stocks a good variety of products but closes too early for a LV hotel (10pm).Overall, the rooms are clean and a bit outdated but have an in-room safe, iron and ironing board. Water pressure is the best I have experienced in a hotel and hot water doesn't seem to be an issue any time of the day (can't say either about the 4 Queens). Non-smoking rooms are available but seem very limited as I have been given a smoking room on 4 of my last 6 visits even though I requested non-smoking when my reservation was made (the front desk doesn't even mention it isn't available when I check in, I just discover it when entering the floor from the elevator.0Overall, a decent value for you money as far as hotels go...there's certainly room for improvement in both amenities and front-desk staffing.I've stayed at the 4 Queens, Golden Nugget, and the Fremont (with it's closet-sized bathrooms!) on a few of my visits and the all are on-par with the Fitz (Golden Nugget may be a notch higher).	
Aug 26 2005	Great place away from the strip	The Fitzgerld turned out to be a fine place to stay. After reading some of the reviews I was skeptial about it. My first time in &quot;Sin City&quot; so I was not sure where this hotel was located. It is about two miles from the Strip but we found lots to do and enjoyed the Freemont Street Experience. The bus runs 24 hours a day to Strip $2.00 each way or $5.00 for a 24 hour pass. The Fitz is an older hotel but was very clean and has been keet well. Over overal lthe service was great. Some of the front desk clerks could use a few customer service lessons. The only issue we had was that the air conditioning unit was loud and unbearable. I phoned and they had the unit changed out in less than an hour. The only draw back is Molly's Resurant located on the 2nd floor. They were short of help and the service there was non existant. The food was okay but there are plenty of places to eat.Beware of the &quot;Free Gift&quot; Promotation. The hotel has these people that will give you $60.00 cash or dinner and a show if you tour their time share properties. If you don't buy (and please don't buy,) you are treated as red head convict step child. They abondoned you and leave you waiting for a shuttle to take you back to the hotel. A 90 min presentation took five hours. They did pay the $60.00 but it was not worth the time it took. All-in-all the Fitz was worth money. No it's not the Ritz but it is far from a flea bag.	
